  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. Under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and related statutes, such as the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957), the penalties for money laundering include:\n\n1. **Criminal Penalties**:\n   - **Imprisonment**: Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison** per violation.\n   - **Fines**: For individuals, fines can be up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds**, whichever is greater. For organizations, fines can reach **$1 million or twice the value of the laundered funds**.\n   - **Additional Penalties**: Convictions may also result in the forfeiture of any property or funds involved in the laundering scheme.\n\n2. **Civil Penalties**:\n   - Civil fines can be imposed even if there is no criminal conviction. These fines may amount to the **value of the laundered funds or $10,000**, whichever is greater.\n\n3. **Enhanced Penalties**:\n   - Involvement in money laundering as part of a **continuing criminal enterprise** or in connection with **terrorism financing** can lead to even harsher penalties, including **life imprisonment**.\n\n4. **Additional Consequences**:\n   - Conviction may result in **loss of professional licenses** (e.g., banking, legal, or accounting licenses).\n   - Individuals may face **restrictions on future employment** in financial institutions or other regulated industries.\n   - International travel may also be restricted.\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors such as the **amount of money laundered**, the **nature of the underlying criminal activity**, and the defendant\u2019s **criminal history**. Prosecutions are typically handled by the **Department of Justice (DOJ)**, and investigations often involve agencies like the **Internal Revenue Service (IRS)**, **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)**, and **Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)**.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
